.SH "NAME"
Mail::DMARC::Report::Receive \- process incoming DMARC reports
.SH "VERSION"
.IX Header "VERSION"
version 1.20200214
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
Receive \s-1DMARC\s0 reports and save them to the report store/database.
.SH "METHODS"
.IX Header "METHODS"
.SS "from_imap, from_file, from_mbox"
.IX Subsection "from_imap, from_file, from_mbox"
These methods are called by dmarc_receive program, which has its own documentation and usage instructions. The methods accept a message (or list of messages) and create an Email::Simple object from each, passing that object to from_email_simple.
.SS "from_email_simple"
.IX Subsection "from_email_simple"
Accepts an Email::Simple message object. Returns the type of \s-1DMARC\s0 report detected or undef if no \s-1DMARC\s0 report was detected.
.PP
When forensic reports are detected, no further processing is done.
.PP
When an aggregate report is detected, the report details are extracted from the message body as well as the Subject field/header and attachment metadata.
.PP
Parsing of the Subject and \s-1MIME\s0 metadata is necessary because the 2013 draft \s-1DMARC\s0 specification does not \s-1REQUIRE\s0 the envelope_to domain name to be included in the \s-1XML\s0 report. For example, the only way to \fBknow\fR that the email which generated this particular report was sent to hotmail.com is to extract the envelope_to domain from the message metadata (Org Name=Microsoft, hotmail.com is not in the \s-1XML\s0). So far, every messsage I have seen has had the envelope_to domain in one location or the other.
.PP
To extract messages from the message body, the \s-1MIME\s0 attachments are decompressed and passed to handle_body.
.SS "handle_body"
.IX Subsection "handle_body"
Accepts a \s-1XML\s0 message, parsing it with XML::LibXML and XPath expressions. The parsed data is stored in a Mail::DMARC::Report object. When the parsing is complete, the report object is saved to the report store.
